The Rğœ‘Z gate

54.9 Î¼s

Passing a qubit through the Rğœ‘Z is equivalent to multiplying its state vector by [100eğœ‘i]. Remember, eiÎ¸=cos(ğœƒ)+isin(ğœƒ).

The Rğœ‘Z gate can be alternatively denoted by, [eâˆ’ğœ‘i/200eğœ‘i/2]. Its just the original matrix, multiplied by eâˆ’ğœ‘i/2. We can do this since multiplication by eâˆ’ğœ‘i/2 is not observable during measurement as its a complex unit and |eiÎ¸|=|cos(ğœƒ)+isin(ğœƒ)|=1. Remember that the abstract value of a complex number a+ib, i.e., |a+ib|=a2+b2 and sin2Î¸+cos2Î¸=1.

Considering a qubit, a|0âŒª+b|0âŒª, passing it through the Rğ¹2Z gate is equivalent to [100eğœ‹i/2] . And since cos(ğ¹2)=0 and sin(ğ¹2)=1, we can rewrite the above as, [100i] [ab].

Whats the difference between the DaggeredBlock and adjoint ' ?

One is a function of Yao, while another of Base julia. Both perform the same operation on their input, but DaggeredBlock is many times faster.
